ook collections in relation to public libraries. Contributors explore libraries at particular moments in their history across a wide range of cases, and includes Alberto Manguel’s account of the Library of Alexandria as well as chapters on library collecting in the middle ages, the libraries of prime ministers and foreign embassies, protest libraries and the slow transformation of university libraries, and the stories of the personal libraries of Virginia Woolf, Robert Duncan, Sheila Watson, Al Purdy and others. The book shows how the history of the library is really a history of collection, consolidation, migration, dispersal, and integration, where each story negotiates private and public spaces. Unpacking the Personal Library builds on and interrogates theories and approaches from library and archive studies, the history of the book, reading, authorship and publishing. Collectively, the chapters articulate a critical poetics of the personal library within its extended social, aesthetic and cultural contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aArchival Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh  aAlexandria.  aArchives.  aAuthorship.  aBooks.  aBooksellers.  aCollections.  aCollectors.  aCultural Studies.  aDigital Humanities.  aDigitization.  aDuncan.  aEducation.  aLibraries.  aLibrary.  aMackenzie King.  aMuseums.  aPrint Collections.  aProtest.  aPurdy.  aSheila Watson.  aWoolf.  abook history, archive studies, literary studies.1 aAnstee, Cameron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamlot, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamlot, Jason, eeditor.4edt